How are you, Rafael?

40
00:02:56,880 --> 00:02:57,880
I'm well, thank you, Mark.

41
00:02:57,880 --> 00:03:01,200
I'm very happy to be on the show with you.

42
00:03:01,200 --> 00:03:06,120
Happy and actually privileged to appreciate this time with you and looking forward to some

43
00:03:06,120 --> 00:03:07,120
interesting discussion.

44
00:03:07,120 --> 00:03:08,120
Yeah.

45
00:03:08,120 --> 00:03:09,120
So am I.

46
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:12,800
I think we're going to get into a really good discussion today.

47
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:19,000
For the listeners, the focus of today's discussion is really around law more than anything else.

48
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:23,480
What are some of the legal things that happen in negotiation, specifically when it comes

49
00:03:23,480 --> 00:03:31,000
to conflict and how to manage conflict in a negotiation or post negotiation?

50
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:34,740
We're going to let the conversation take us where it needs to.

51
00:03:34,740 --> 00:03:40,440
It's going to be loose and conversational, as it always is, and I want to get you to

52
00:03:40,440 --> 00:03:43,160
know Rafael a little bit better.

53
00:03:43,160 --> 00:03:48,840
So Rafael, maybe we'll just start off with a bit of a personal history, your background,

54
00:03:48,840 --> 00:03:50,960
and why you started your practice.

55
00:03:50,960 --> 00:03:51,960
Great.

56
00:03:51,960 --> 00:03:58,360
Okay, Mark, as the youngest of four siblings, so I had to learn how to negotiate and manage

57
00:03:58,360 --> 00:04:04,840
conflict from a very, very young age, but as I grow older and I started studying law

58
00:04:04,840 --> 00:04:13,080
and getting involved in the real world out there, I became concerned about the legal

59
00:04:13,080 --> 00:04:18,320
system, particularly the way we see it played out in the United States, which is an incredibly

60
00:04:18,320 --> 00:04:25,200
religious society, and in fact, it reminds me, as in Copenhagen a few years ago, working

61
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:30,040
with the European Union, and one of the European lawyers asked me, and they said, why is it

62
00:04:30,040 --> 00:04:34,160
when we're doing work with Americans, we're trying to make deals with Americans, they

63
00:04:34,160 --> 00:04:41,320
walk into the room with an army of lawyers and with reams of contracts, and they couldn't

64
00:04:41,320 --> 00:04:43,320
quite understand it.

65
00:04:43,320 --> 00:04:46,520
My response to them was, well, there's a bit of a difference here between Europeans

66
00:04:46,520 --> 00:04:48,160
and Americans.

67
00:04:48,160 --> 00:04:52,680
In America, we do business with people even though we don't trust them, so trust is not

68
00:04:52,680 --> 00:05:00,040
a prerequisite to necessarily do business, built very, very tightly, but we don't need

69
00:05:00,040 --> 00:05:06,260
trust in America because we work very, very closely with a very, very strong legal language

70
00:05:06,260 --> 00:05:09,900
in contracts and a very strong system to enforce it.

71
00:05:09,900 --> 00:05:14,000
In Europe, I said to them, you guys only do business or try to do business mostly with

72
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,640
people you trust, and you'll try to build that trust beforehand.

73
00:05:17,640 --> 00:05:23,040
In America, because of that fact, I think it's a very religious society, and if there

74
00:05:23,040 --> 00:05:27,600
is a breach, it goes straight to litigation, which is not a great thing we'll discuss

75
00:05:27,600 --> 00:05:28,600
a little later.

76
00:05:28,600 --> 00:05:35,640
When I saw that, I realized that I wanted to be involved in helping people deal with

77
00:05:35,640 --> 00:05:40,840
disputes, helping people make negotiations, but in a much more optimal way in which

78
00:05:40,840 --> 00:05:45,820
we can resolve our disputes and make deals and negotiate in ways where we are not pitting

79
00:05:45,820 --> 00:05:48,560
the relationship against the substance.

80
00:05:48,560 --> 00:05:56,480
We can be respectful and fair in the relationship dealings, but still at the same time being

81
00:05:56,480 --> 00:06:02,480
very hard on the substantial issues of the negotiation or the dispute resolution.

82
00:06:02,480 --> 00:06:07,720
When I started this, this was an emerging field back in the 90s, mediation was just

83
00:06:07,720 --> 00:06:13,680
taking off and looking for alternative dispute resolution methods was taking off.

84
00:06:13,680 --> 00:06:18,880
It just seemed a perfect fit for me, and that's how originally I got involved.

85
00:06:18,880 --> 00:06:19,880
Awesome.

86
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:22,880
Very, very cool.

87
00:06:22,880 --> 00:06:28,640
A lot of the time I get questions from listeners and from clients about what are the most

88
00:06:28,640 --> 00:06:35,560
common issues that you see, and while that's a great question, there's certainly a number

89
00:06:35,560 --> 00:06:42,600
of issues that I see on an ongoing basis, but I'd be interested to hear from you.

90
00:06:42,600 --> 00:06:47,880
In your practice, what are some of the most common negotiation questions that you get

91
00:06:47,880 --> 00:06:49,960
on an ongoing basis?

92
00:06:49,960 --> 00:06:56,240
Well, oftentimes people, some things that people sometimes say to me just happened in

93
00:06:56,240 --> 00:07:03,380
fact yesterday, I get so emotional in negotiations and I sometimes get angry and I sometimes

94
00:07:03,380 --> 00:07:11,020
get upset, and any time that a person feels his vital interests of being threatened, he's

95
00:07:11,020 --> 00:07:18,140
going to get emotional, and typically what happens over there is that if one party gets emotional,

96
00:07:18,140 --> 00:07:26,140
it triggers emotion, and the other party spirals down into an action, reaction, and counter-reaction

97
00:07:26,140 --> 00:07:27,140
sort of situation.

98
00:07:27,140 --> 00:07:31,700
So oftentimes, interestingly, I'll be asked, how can I make sure to go into that negotiation

99
00:07:31,700 --> 00:07:39,740
with grace and composure and not be triggered by these sort of hot buttons that may set

100
00:07:39,740 --> 00:07:43,020
me off and derail the entire negotiation?

101
00:07:43,020 --> 00:07:45,660
So sometimes that's an issue.

102
00:07:45,660 --> 00:07:50,900
Another issue question that I get involved in, how can I deal with people that are being

103
00:07:50,900 --> 00:07:51,900
unreasonable?

104
00:07:51,900 --> 00:07:56,340
A great one is, how can I make them hear me?

105
00:07:56,340 --> 00:08:00,100
How can I make them listen to me?

106
00:08:00,100 --> 00:08:06,820
Which is another great one, and of course the question is based on an entirely wrong premise,

107
00:08:06,820 --> 00:08:11,500
but those are the sort of questions that come up very often, very typically, other than

108
00:08:11,500 --> 00:08:16,580
we'll be involved in a specific negotiation and we're working on substantial details of

109
00:08:16,580 --> 00:08:21,700
the particular negotiation, and then obviously sort of questions come up related to that.

110
00:08:21,700 --> 00:08:24,620
But in terms of the process, it's usually sort of, how can I make sure they listen

111
00:08:24,620 --> 00:08:31,460
and why they're being so unreasonable, why aren't they agreeing with me, why they're

112
00:08:31,460 --> 00:08:35,460
being so unfair, that sort of thing.

113
00:08:35,460 --> 00:08:39,660
So how do you answer the question then of how can I make them hear me?

114
00:08:39,660 --> 00:08:48,180
Because I feel like a lot of the time, many people who enter a negotiation feel like their

115
00:08:48,180 --> 00:08:56,620
argument is based on very clear logic, and when they feel like someone isn't listening

116
00:08:56,620 --> 00:09:01,140
to them, that's obviously when they get very frustrated.

117
00:09:01,140 --> 00:09:04,860
So how do you answer the question of how can I make them hear me?

118
00:09:04,860 --> 00:09:10,700
So that's a great question, and again, as I sort of alluded to, the answer is a bit

119
00:09:10,700 --> 00:09:12,740
counterintuitive.

120
00:09:12,740 --> 00:09:19,060
So first of all, the studies have shown that in normal conversation, typically about 70%

121
00:09:19,060 --> 00:09:23,940
on average of what the talker is saying, the listener is missing, and the reason the listener

122
00:09:23,940 --> 00:09:30,580
is missing that is because he's busy framing his response while the talker is talking.

123
00:09:30,580 --> 00:09:37,180
So I've got to make sure when I'm talking to somebody that I'm liberating them from trying

124
00:09:37,180 --> 00:09:41,540
to think about their response or what they're going to say while I'm talking, because if

125
00:09:41,540 --> 00:09:44,500
that's going to happen, it's a waste of time for me to talk.

126
00:09:44,500 --> 00:09:49,900
So for that to happen, I've got to first make sure before I even begin talking, if I want

127
00:09:49,900 --> 00:09:55,220
to really be listened, I've got to first start off the conversation on their side and

128
00:09:55,220 --> 00:09:58,620
say, Mark, tell me what your initial thoughts on this issue is, and make sure that you

129
00:09:58,620 --> 00:10:03,020
feel adequately heard, adequately understood, and I'm using active listening to make

130
00:10:03,020 --> 00:10:05,660
sure that you really know that I've got you.

131
00:10:05,660 --> 00:10:09,780
And then once I say having understood you, it would make sense for me to share some

132
00:10:09,780 --> 00:10:11,060
of my ideas with you.

133
00:10:11,060 --> 00:10:14,180
Now you liberate it to listen to me.

134
00:10:14,180 --> 00:10:17,500
But until that time, you're too busy thinking about what you're going to say.

135
00:10:17,500 --> 00:10:21,780
So paradoxically, the way to make sure that I'm being heard and I'm being understood

136
00:10:21,780 --> 00:10:26,660
is to first make sure that the other party feels heard and understood as well.

137
00:10:26,660 --> 00:10:33,700
Many people are afraid to do that because they think that understanding, demonstrating,

138
00:10:33,700 --> 00:10:36,020
understanding is tantamount to agreeing.

139
00:10:36,020 --> 00:10:37,020
And that's not true.

140
00:10:37,020 --> 00:10:38,020
I can understand you immaculately.

141
00:10:38,020 --> 00:10:40,380
It doesn't mean I agree to you.

142
00:10:40,380 --> 00:10:43,660
And in negotiations, I'll say to the other party very often, I'll say, you know, before

143
00:10:43,660 --> 00:10:47,460
I'm suspending judgment, I've not yet made a decision.

144
00:10:47,460 --> 00:10:52,140
But before I can make an informed decision, I need to understand more about what your

145
00:10:52,140 --> 00:10:53,260
position is.

146
00:10:53,260 --> 00:10:55,220
Please go ahead and try to explain that to me.

147
00:10:55,220 --> 00:11:00,220
And I'll spend quite a lot of time on their side while they're doing it.

148
00:11:00,220 --> 00:11:04,980
And another reason that that's important is because if I say something after I've

149
00:11:04,980 --> 00:11:09,740
demonstrated a very, very robust understanding of what it is that you're saying, you're

150
00:11:09,740 --> 00:11:13,060
much more receptive to what I'm saying because you know that I've understood you.

151
00:11:13,060 --> 00:11:18,260
So my mentor, Roger Fisher in Harvard used to argue cases in the Supreme Court.

152
00:11:18,260 --> 00:11:22,820
And interestingly, when he would argue those cases, Mark, he would start off arguing those

153
00:11:22,820 --> 00:11:28,300
cases, making the argument of his opposing counsel.

154
00:11:28,300 --> 00:11:33,180
The only thing is he would argue it more compellingly and more eloquently than his

155
00:11:33,180 --> 00:11:37,580
opponents argued it until the judge would get confused.

156
00:11:37,580 --> 00:11:42,100
And the judge would say, Mr. Fisher, whose side are you on?

157
00:11:42,100 --> 00:11:44,460
And Roger would say, bear with me on, I'm getting there.

158
00:11:44,460 --> 00:11:49,980
And having often demonstrated incredible understanding of the other side, he would

159
00:11:49,980 --> 00:11:54,500
then say, and your honor is a different way of looking at this as well.

160
00:11:54,500 --> 00:11:56,140
And then present his story.

161
00:11:56,140 --> 00:12:00,620
Notice though, he didn't say, but he said, and because that is the great eraser that

162
00:12:00,620 --> 00:12:02,300
erases everything that came before it.

163
00:12:02,300 --> 00:12:03,300
You're wonderful.

164
00:12:03,300 --> 00:12:04,300
You're brilliant.

165
00:12:04,300 --> 00:12:05,300
You're gorgeous.

166
00:12:05,300 --> 00:12:11,900
So there are many, many advantages to make sure that I'm first spending a lot of time

167
00:12:11,900 --> 00:12:16,220
on your side, understanding you, demonstrating that understanding, that I can argue your

168
00:12:16,220 --> 00:12:18,620
case better than you can argue it yourself.

169
00:12:18,620 --> 00:12:21,060
And then you're much more receptive to listen to me.

170
00:12:21,060 --> 00:12:25,060
And that's a real way to get hurt.

171
00:12:25,060 --> 00:12:28,940
I love what you said there in terms of liberating them to listen to you.

172
00:12:28,940 --> 00:12:32,900
I think that's a great way to think of it because essentially they're a prisoner

173
00:12:32,900 --> 00:12:35,100
to their own thoughts until you do that.

174
00:12:35,100 --> 00:12:36,100
That's right.

175
00:12:36,100 --> 00:12:38,460
And people come into negotiations ready to assert their demands.

176
00:12:38,460 --> 00:12:40,260
And that's one of the big mistakes that people do.

177
00:12:40,260 --> 00:12:44,980
They come in and they say, we demand this, we want that, this is what we want.

178
00:12:44,980 --> 00:12:47,740
And very few people respond positively to that sort of thing.

179
00:12:47,740 --> 00:12:50,660
And that's why many negotiations go south.

180
00:12:50,660 --> 00:12:54,990
Yeah, really good advice.

181
00:12:54,990 --> 00:12:57,270
And is that the source of conflict?

182
00:12:57,270 --> 00:13:03,510
When someone feels like they haven't been listened to or understood, is that ultimately

183
00:13:03,510 --> 00:13:04,670
the source of conflict?

184
00:13:04,670 --> 00:13:08,550
Or what's generally the source of conflict in a negotiation?

185
00:13:08,550 --> 00:13:11,870
Mark, that's a very broad question because there's so many sources of conflict.

186
00:13:11,870 --> 00:13:13,990
I'll give you an example from this week, actually.

187
00:13:13,990 --> 00:13:16,790
So we did a mediation this week.

188
00:13:16,790 --> 00:13:21,710
It was quite a complex real estate dispute.

189
00:13:21,710 --> 00:13:26,270
There were seven, besides me, there were seven parties in the room.

190
00:13:26,270 --> 00:13:30,550
And we actually, in five and a half hours, we actually reached agreements.

191
00:13:30,550 --> 00:13:31,550
It was wonderful.

192
00:13:32,310 --> 00:13:33,310
Nobody could believe it.

193
00:13:33,310 --> 00:13:35,310
We reached a very good agreement.

194
00:13:35,310 --> 00:13:43,070
Then yesterday, the attorneys of one of the parties called me and they said that the records

195
00:13:43,070 --> 00:13:49,910
that they received that showed certain numbers related to the real estate were not accurate.

196
00:13:49,910 --> 00:13:53,070
And this attorney was ready to go for the jugular.

197
00:13:53,070 --> 00:13:56,510
Our client's pulling out of the deal, he wants this, he wants that, he wants the other,

198
00:13:56,510 --> 00:14:04,350
he wants to cut the price by 25% or whatever it was.

199
00:14:04,350 --> 00:14:05,950
So the attorneys said, should I contact them?

200
00:14:05,950 --> 00:14:09,230
I said, don't you dare.

201
00:14:09,230 --> 00:14:13,190
Because they would have got in, again, with an emotional thing, you cooked us, you cheated

202
00:14:13,190 --> 00:14:16,350
us, and that would have just unraveled the entire agreement.

203
00:14:16,350 --> 00:14:17,350
I said, let me deal with this.

204
00:14:17,350 --> 00:14:18,670
I'll talk to the other side.

205
00:14:18,670 --> 00:14:23,310
Well, it turns out, Mark, that the records that they provided were actually the wrong

206
00:14:23,310 --> 00:14:24,310
records.

207
00:14:25,030 --> 00:14:28,150
The most recently updated records.

208
00:14:28,150 --> 00:14:34,150
And once we found the correct records, everything was there as it should have been.

209
00:14:34,150 --> 00:14:39,510
So there's an example of a potential cause of conflict, which is just a basic misunderstanding.

210
00:14:39,510 --> 00:14:43,550
So before we go down that path, we need to make sure that we have the facts that

211
00:14:43,550 --> 00:14:48,030
we need, and we have the documentation that we need, and it's all accurate.

212
00:14:48,030 --> 00:14:53,990
But people jump to conclusions and assumptions, and then they act on those assumptions.

213
00:14:53,990 --> 00:14:59,310
The more simplistic example of that is where people confuse impact with intent.

214
00:14:59,310 --> 00:15:05,590
So because you did something which impacted me in a hurtful way, I automatically assumed

215
00:15:05,590 --> 00:15:09,390
that was your intent.

216
00:15:09,390 --> 00:15:14,590
So there are many different causes that could trigger conflict.

217
00:15:14,590 --> 00:15:21,070
And if you know how to deal and manage with conflict, the root cause of what's causing

218
00:15:21,070 --> 00:15:25,030
the conflict, what triggered that conflict, is less important than the process that

219
00:15:25,030 --> 00:15:26,870
could be used to resolve that conflict.

220
00:15:26,870 --> 00:15:31,110
So yesterday, for example, I didn't argue the process that I used was, instead of going

221
00:15:31,110 --> 00:15:34,790
to attack the other side, I called the other attorney up, and I said, I'm sure there's

222
00:15:34,790 --> 00:15:36,790
a misunderstanding here.

223
00:15:36,790 --> 00:15:39,590
This is what the other side's claiming.

224
00:15:39,590 --> 00:15:42,030
Is there anything we need to clarify?

225
00:15:42,030 --> 00:15:47,030
So I did not pass on the entire message that I got from the first attorney, I just

226
00:15:47,030 --> 00:15:51,190
used a very, very decontaminated, detoxified message.

227
00:15:51,190 --> 00:15:53,390
And I said, I'm sure there's a misunderstanding here.

228
00:15:53,390 --> 00:15:54,390
What can we do?

229
00:15:54,550 --> 00:15:57,590
I think they must have sent the wrong record.

230
00:15:57,590 --> 00:15:58,750
And that took care of the whole problem.

231
00:15:58,750 --> 00:16:03,030
So in terms of how we approach it is more important than what the actual cause of it

232
00:16:03,030 --> 00:16:04,030
is.

233
00:16:04,030 --> 00:16:05,030
Yeah.

234
00:16:05,030 --> 00:16:14,710
You know, you speak very deeply about the cost of conflict and what the cost of conflict could

