00:18:19,750 --> 00:18:24,550
was a slight misunderstanding between countries, they would immediately go to war.

265
00:18:24,550 --> 00:18:29,950
So that's basically the social equivalent of how people go to straight litigation without

266
00:18:29,950 --> 00:18:32,790
using any diplomatic efforts.

267
00:18:32,790 --> 00:18:37,510
And the costs of those are absolutely enormous in so many different ways.

268
00:18:37,510 --> 00:18:41,950
And that's one of the reasons that I find passion in my work, because we're able to

269
00:18:41,950 --> 00:18:48,910
save people so much, in terms of resolution, that not only keeps them out of court, but

270
00:18:48,910 --> 00:18:52,870
very, very often actually keeps the working relationship.

271
00:18:52,870 --> 00:18:59,190
So we've done resolutions, mediations and negotiations, where there's a bit of dispute,

272
00:18:59,190 --> 00:19:04,060
but at the end of the day, the parties continue doing business together.

273
00:19:04,060 --> 00:19:06,260
Good advice.

274
00:19:06,260 --> 00:19:14,220
And so is there something that people can do to, because it seems to be a very reactionary

275
00:19:14,220 --> 00:19:22,820
response when we get into that state, that emotional state when it comes to, you've breached

276
00:19:22,820 --> 00:19:28,400
and now I'm really upset, so we're going straight to litigation.

277
00:19:28,400 --> 00:19:36,760
Is there something that people can do to think about or habits to develop in order to

278
00:19:36,760 --> 00:19:44,880
avoid getting into that emotional state or that mental state of reactionary approach?

279
00:19:44,880 --> 00:19:45,880
Yes.

280
00:19:45,880 --> 00:19:53,560
We always tell our clients that we're working with is that in negotiations, it's much more

281
00:19:53,560 --> 00:19:59,400
important to keep the other party off the defensive, not to make them defensive.

282
00:19:59,400 --> 00:20:04,480
We can accomplish a lot more when they are being defensive.

283
00:20:04,480 --> 00:20:08,920
And I think that's got to be the initial point when we are approaching the other side

284
00:20:08,920 --> 00:20:15,240
of who we maybe suspect breached a contract, is not to call them up or send a lawsuit

285
00:20:15,240 --> 00:20:19,040
and say, okay, you guys breached the contract, we can no longer trust you.

286
00:20:19,040 --> 00:20:22,160
But to approach it from a more diplomatic side, and again, I'm sure there's been

287
00:20:22,160 --> 00:20:27,000
some sort of misunderstanding here, we've noticed that we've noticed that.

288
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:31,560
What ideas do you have in terms of how we might deal with this?

289
00:20:31,560 --> 00:20:36,200
And I find many, many times when we approach it in that way, it opens up some productive

290
00:20:36,200 --> 00:20:38,800
discussion, some productive conversation.

291
00:20:38,800 --> 00:20:45,720
People at the core, for the most part, Mark, are reasonable, rational people.

292
00:20:45,720 --> 00:20:49,520
But they do become raving lunatics when the vital, as I mentioned earlier, the vital

293
00:20:49,520 --> 00:20:54,720
interests of being threatened, of where they're being accused, where they don't feel that

294
00:20:54,720 --> 00:20:59,800
accusations are appropriate or accurate, and that's when people sort of become defensive

295
00:20:59,800 --> 00:21:02,160
and that's when they become lunatics.

296
00:21:02,160 --> 00:21:10,440
But people at the core are rational, logical people with whom one can reason.

297
00:21:10,440 --> 00:21:14,160
I don't know if you're aware of my book, Working with Difficult People, but in the

298
00:21:14,160 --> 00:21:19,240
book I make the point that when I'm dealing with a difficult person, my first question

299
00:21:19,240 --> 00:21:25,080
that I ask myself is what am I doing that's enabling them and allowing them to be difficult,

300
00:21:25,080 --> 00:21:30,640
and what new ingredient can I mix into this interpersonal dynamic with them that could

301
00:21:30,640 --> 00:21:33,360
change that?

302
00:21:33,360 --> 00:21:35,080
Because they're difficult from my perspective.

303
00:21:35,080 --> 00:21:38,280
If you ask their friends or you ask their spouse, you ask their family, is this a difficult

304
00:21:38,280 --> 00:21:39,280
person?

305
00:21:39,280 --> 00:21:40,280
Is it a pathologically difficult person?

306
00:21:40,280 --> 00:21:43,520
I say, I don't know what you're talking about.

307
00:21:43,520 --> 00:21:49,530
There's difficulty in this situation and I can control that.

308
00:21:49,530 --> 00:21:52,080
Interesting.

309
00:21:52,080 --> 00:21:58,120
What do you think that people can do, given that there's conflict, ultimately there's

310
00:21:58,120 --> 00:22:05,320
always going to be, it doesn't have to be always, but there's often conflict in contract

311
00:22:05,320 --> 00:22:09,520
negotiations or breach of contract discussions.

312
00:22:09,520 --> 00:22:14,440
What can people do to avoid conflict in those discussions?

313
00:22:14,440 --> 00:22:18,520
We speak about the whole dispute resolution process.

314
00:22:18,520 --> 00:22:23,520
Could we be including that dispute resolution process and that language in our agreement

315
00:22:23,520 --> 00:22:30,560
so that if we get to a point of conflict, we have a process to follow that is able to

316
00:22:30,560 --> 00:22:35,800
force people out of that emotional state into a process that they can follow to help them

317
00:22:35,800 --> 00:22:37,280
through that dispute resolution?

318
00:22:37,280 --> 00:22:42,120
You know, Mark, I'm a very, very big advocate of ADR clauses in contracts.

319
00:22:42,120 --> 00:22:47,000
The reason is it's much easier for us to talk about a potential conflict and how we

320
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:51,040
are going to deal with it before we become embroiled in it.

321
00:22:51,040 --> 00:22:53,880
Once you're embroiled in the conflict, you know, that's when people don't see things

322
00:22:53,880 --> 00:22:57,920
quite as rationally necessarily, particularly if it's sort of attack and counter-attack.

323
00:22:57,920 --> 00:23:02,200
So it's certainly much more productive and easier to talk about what will we do in

324
00:23:02,200 --> 00:23:07,360
a situation of conflict before that conflict actually arises, and then to make sure that

325
00:23:07,360 --> 00:23:09,920
there's processes that are set into place.

326
00:23:09,920 --> 00:23:16,920
And in many different ways that these alternative dispute resolution or ADR clauses can be structured

327
00:23:17,840 --> 00:23:21,240
and tailored to the particular situation.

328
00:23:21,240 --> 00:23:25,840
And you know, we've done some useful ones ourselves and actually seen them be implemented

329
00:23:25,840 --> 00:23:29,520
in some dispute later on that arise.

330
00:23:29,520 --> 00:23:35,040
And the idea of an ADR clause is essentially to retard the litigation process or to eliminate

331
00:23:35,040 --> 00:23:40,800
it completely through arbitration, which one has to be careful about because as you probably

332
00:23:40,800 --> 00:23:45,320
know, arbitration, at least in the U.S., can't be appealed on very, very limited

333
00:23:45,320 --> 00:23:48,840
basis as can be appealed.

334
00:23:48,840 --> 00:23:55,080
But nevertheless, you know, many ADR clauses will stipulate arbitration.

335
00:23:55,080 --> 00:24:01,460
So if we have a method built into our contract that we both agree essentially that if we do

336
00:24:01,460 --> 00:24:05,360
reach a point where there's a dispute over something, we will make sure we will resolve

337
00:24:05,360 --> 00:24:08,680
it and use litigation as a very, very last resort.

338
00:24:08,680 --> 00:24:13,440
I mean, that can save, just that clause in the contract can save those companies a

339
00:24:13,440 --> 00:24:15,120
lot of money.

340
00:24:15,120 --> 00:24:18,640
And if ultimately there is some dispute over a contract, which does happen many times, as

341
00:24:18,640 --> 00:24:19,640
you know.

342
00:24:19,640 --> 00:24:31,320
Yeah, I find the importance of having a dispute resolution clause in agreement cannot be understated.

343
00:24:31,320 --> 00:24:37,200
I feel like, you know, there's been enough situations that I've been in where we fully

344
00:24:37,200 --> 00:24:46,720
realize that it's significantly less costly to come to some sort of a business solution

345
00:24:46,720 --> 00:24:50,040
as opposed to some sort of a legal solution.

346
00:24:50,040 --> 00:24:57,560
And it's certainly going to be better on the relationship, I find, if we have those clauses

347
00:24:57,560 --> 00:24:58,560
in place.

348
00:24:58,560 --> 00:24:59,560
That's right.

349
00:24:59,560 --> 00:25:05,200
You mentioned this difference between the legal side with the solution side.

350
00:25:05,200 --> 00:25:10,880
It's actually interesting because I did a mediation not long ago, where it's a fascinating

351
00:25:10,880 --> 00:25:11,880
mediation as well.

352
00:25:11,880 --> 00:25:16,280
So, you know, that's what I enjoy about mediation because it's, you know, when you work the process,

353
00:25:16,280 --> 00:25:17,600
it just works like magic.

354
00:25:17,600 --> 00:25:18,600
It's amazing.

355
00:25:18,600 --> 00:25:21,040
This is also a major dispute, a major business dispute.

356
00:25:21,040 --> 00:25:27,720
And the lawyers came in with the clients and the lawyers started arguing the law.

357
00:25:27,720 --> 00:25:32,840
And you know, I let that happen because my thinking was that there had to be some

358
00:25:32,840 --> 00:25:39,040
doubt and dissonance sort of brought into that room with each attorney realizing there's

359
00:25:39,040 --> 00:25:40,880
another argument here.

360
00:25:40,880 --> 00:25:42,680
And how might the judge look at that?

361
00:25:42,680 --> 00:25:46,360
Because until that happens, each attorney thinks that he has a watertight case.

362
00:25:46,360 --> 00:25:50,280
And it's only when the attorneys and the clients hear the other side's case, they start asking

363
00:25:50,280 --> 00:25:53,800
them now, then I might say something to one of the attorneys and say, let's imagine that

364
00:25:53,800 --> 00:25:57,040
it's six months down the road, a year down the road, two years down the road,

365
00:25:57,040 --> 00:25:59,040
and you've lost this case.

366
00:25:59,040 --> 00:26:02,760
What possible reason would you be able to think of as to why you might lose?

367
00:26:02,760 --> 00:26:05,720
And that oftentimes generates some interesting discussion, throw some doubt and dissonance

368
00:26:05,720 --> 00:26:06,720
in there.

369
00:26:06,720 --> 00:26:09,280
But my point is, as long as this discussion was happening, it happened for about an hour

370
00:26:09,280 --> 00:26:14,040
and a half in this particular mediation, the mediation was not going nowhere.

371
00:26:14,040 --> 00:26:18,120
And we could have gone like that for three days and no resolution would have ever happened.

