00:26:34,400 --> 00:26:39,440
And some fascinating information came out that was a revelation to me, which is what

378
00:26:39,440 --> 00:26:44,280
typically unlocks the negotiation when you find those little nuggets of revelations.

379
00:26:44,280 --> 00:26:47,760
And then at that point, we were able to resolve it.

380
00:26:47,760 --> 00:26:55,480
So arguing the legal strengths and weaknesses of the case typically doesn't resolve an issue

381
00:26:55,480 --> 00:26:58,040
in negotiation or in mediation.

382
00:27:01,160 --> 00:27:03,720
Yeah, I fully agree with you.

383
00:27:03,720 --> 00:27:10,320
I think, you know, the more we can try and maintain that sort of rational outlook instead

384
00:27:10,320 --> 00:27:18,600
of responding with the immediate legal response, it's only going to benefit us in the future.

385
00:27:18,600 --> 00:27:19,600
That's right.

386
00:27:19,600 --> 00:27:23,880
And the legal response will stifle and inhibit any creative thinking.

387
00:27:23,880 --> 00:27:29,960
So you've got to move out of that legal argument arena to start looking for the creativity,

388
00:27:29,960 --> 00:27:33,280
the creativity in the negotiation and in the resolution.

389
00:27:33,280 --> 00:27:39,280
You know, I'd love to tell the story, which I'm sure you might have heard about the sheik,

390
00:27:39,280 --> 00:27:42,000
the Arab sheik who had 17 camels.

391
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:43,000
Did you ever hear that story?

392
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:44,000
No, I hadn't.

393
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:49,560
Yeah, so he writes in his will an interesting sort of division and you know, in some of

394
00:27:49,560 --> 00:27:53,720
those cultures, the oldest son obviously has certain rights over the other sons and so

395
00:27:53,720 --> 00:27:54,720
on.

396
00:27:54,720 --> 00:27:56,280
There's a certain hierarchy over there.

397
00:27:56,280 --> 00:28:02,520
So he leaves the oldest son, he decides to leave the oldest son one half of his camels.

398
00:28:02,520 --> 00:28:07,920
He wants to leave his second son a third of his camels and he wants to leave his youngest

399
00:28:07,920 --> 00:28:09,720
son one ninth of his camels.

400
00:28:09,720 --> 00:28:17,880
And of course, the problem is 17 isn't divisible by 9, 3 or 2.

401
00:28:17,880 --> 00:28:23,520
So they go to a mediator to resolve this issue and the mediator immediately sees the

402
00:28:23,520 --> 00:28:24,520
problem.

403
00:28:24,520 --> 00:28:31,080
How are we going to divide 17 camels by half a third and a ninth?

404
00:28:31,080 --> 00:28:35,280
Mediator asks them if they happen to have a neighbor who might have a camel.

405
00:28:35,280 --> 00:28:36,280
And they said, yes, we do.

406
00:28:36,280 --> 00:28:38,760
And the mediator says, we'll go borrow a camel from him.

407
00:28:38,760 --> 00:28:44,160
We'll make sure to get it back to him before nightfall this evening and bring it here.

408
00:28:44,160 --> 00:28:48,200
So the brothers go off and they go to the neighbor and they borrow this camel and

409
00:28:48,200 --> 00:28:51,160
they bring the camel back to where the mediator is.

410
00:28:51,160 --> 00:28:53,800
And now they've got the 17 plus the borrowed ones.

411
00:28:53,800 --> 00:28:59,400
So now there's altogether 18 camels sitting there.

412
00:28:59,400 --> 00:29:03,560
So the mediator says, well, let's start dividing and it gives the half of the camels to the

413
00:29:03,560 --> 00:29:04,560
oldest son.

414
00:29:04,560 --> 00:29:05,560
Well, half of 18 is 9.

415
00:29:05,560 --> 00:29:10,520
And he says, okay, we've got to give a third of the camels to the second son.

416
00:29:10,520 --> 00:29:12,880
A third of 18 is 6.

417
00:29:12,880 --> 00:29:14,960
So 9 and 6 is 15.

418
00:29:14,960 --> 00:29:19,480
And then he says, well, now we have to give a ninth of the camels to the youngest son.

419
00:29:19,480 --> 00:29:22,480
One ninth of 18 is 2.

420
00:29:22,480 --> 00:29:30,160
So if you add that up, you've got 9 plus 6 is 15, plus 2 is 17.

421
00:29:30,160 --> 00:29:34,400
And now they have the one camel, 18th camel, left over that they can return to its original

422
00:29:34,400 --> 00:29:35,880
owner.

423
00:29:35,880 --> 00:29:38,200
And they've resolved the problem.

424
00:29:38,200 --> 00:29:40,560
And they've resolved it very creatively.

425
00:29:40,560 --> 00:29:46,000
And in negotiations and mediations, what I always like to speak about and look for

426
00:29:46,080 --> 00:29:54,840
is that proverbial 18th camel, that little creative idea or that bit of information or

427
00:29:54,840 --> 00:30:00,040
whatever it happens to be that just unlocks the negotiation and allows us to move forward.

428
00:30:00,360 --> 00:30:05,280
And we see this negotiation time and time again, I was recently in a mediation where

429
00:30:06,720 --> 00:30:09,400
again, the dispute seemed to everybody to be intractable.

430
00:30:09,400 --> 00:30:11,080
Nobody thought this would settle.

431
00:30:11,600 --> 00:30:20,040
And I heard one thing, it was a small sentence embedded in a whole diatribe of information.

432
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:25,800
And I was listening very carefully and I took that one sentence and took it out and

433
00:30:26,200 --> 00:30:29,960
captured it, fed it back to them and started digging into that issue.

434
00:30:30,160 --> 00:30:34,840
And that opened up and unlocked the entire negotiation, which led to resolution.

435
00:30:35,720 --> 00:30:39,920
So we always want to make sure to be looking for that 18th camel in negotiation.

436
00:30:39,920 --> 00:30:45,080
So being involved in legal posturing and legal arguments, that inhibits us and that

437
00:30:45,240 --> 00:30:49,160
prevents us from seeing that 18th camel.

438
00:30:50,800 --> 00:30:51,560
Great story.

439
00:30:52,160 --> 00:30:57,000
I think there's a lot to be learned from listening.

440
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:03,200
I mean, the piece of advice that I get and that the listeners get over and over and

441
00:31:03,200 --> 00:31:09,480
over again on this show, it seems to keep popping up, is listen, like actively

442
00:31:10,040 --> 00:31:13,320
listen, shut your mouth, don't do anything else.

443
00:31:13,400 --> 00:31:15,600
Just listen to what the other party is saying.

444
00:31:15,960 --> 00:31:21,160
And in that process, you'll be able to uncover a significant amount more

445
00:31:21,160 --> 00:31:28,360
information than if you're thinking about your response to what the person is saying.

446
00:31:28,560 --> 00:31:30,040
Or we're asserting your position.

447
00:31:30,240 --> 00:31:32,160
Yes, or we're asserting your position.

448
00:31:32,160 --> 00:31:35,560
So actually listen to what the other party is saying.

449
00:31:35,560 --> 00:31:40,040
And if that means that you stop what you're doing and write down what the other

450
00:31:40,040 --> 00:31:44,280
party is saying so that you can actively listen and lean in, then you're going to

451
00:31:44,280 --> 00:31:47,920
get a much, much better response.

452
00:31:48,280 --> 00:31:50,960
And not only that, actually, Mark, it goes even beyond that.

453
00:31:50,960 --> 00:31:56,040
And that is that paradoxically, you are far more in control of any

454
00:31:56,040 --> 00:32:01,080
conversation, far more in control when you're listening and asking clarifying

455
00:32:01,080 --> 00:32:06,360
questions, as opposed to when you're trying to speak and assert your position

456
00:32:06,360 --> 00:32:10,000
and demands, you're so much more in control of that conversation, because you

457
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:11,480
can funnel that conversation.

458
00:32:11,720 --> 00:32:14,440
And when you speak about listening, obviously, active listening is a very,

